But one opponent of the plan, Wayne Prospect, a former Suffolk
County legislator and now a consultant to the Hauppauge Industrial
Association, accused Kessel of distorting the energy commission's
actions. ``What Lipa is trying to do, shamelessly, is tell the
public this is a done deal when it is far from it,'' Prospect said.
In a draft of its order for a review of prices in the
power-supply contract, the five-member energy commission said
hearings were necessary to protect the interests of Lilco's
customers. ``Our preliminary analysis of the proposed rate
indicates that it has not been shown to be just and reasonable, and
may be unjust, unreasonable, unduly discriminatory or preferential
or otherwise unlawful.''
Although the commission's hearings could take months, Kessel
said that its review was a standard procedure. He said there was
nothing to stop the governor's plan from proceeding in advance of
the hearings, with retroactive adjustments made according to
anything that the federal commission might impose.
Although Kessel claimed that the commission's review could not
upset the governor's plan, the opponents disputed him and said the
plan was still vulnerable.
Now the plan's proponents are focusing on their next goal of
winning favorable rulings from the Internal Revenue Service, Kessel
said. Pataki is bolstered by the bipartisan support of New York's
two senators, Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat, and Alfonse
D'Amato, a Republican.
The governor's plan seems to have gained momentum lately. Last
week, the state Public Service Commission approved Lilco's planned
merger with Brooklyn Union Gas, which advocates consider an allied
move that will add to the potential rate savings.
While opposition to the Pataki plan has grown in Suffolk,
bipartisan backing for it is now emerging in neighboring Nassau. In
a rare split between the two counties, Nassau officials last month
went to court supporting the plan as intervenors in litigation
filed by the Suffolk County Legislature to block it.
